\binom{15}{10} &= 2\binom{12}{8}+2\binom{11}{8}+\binom{12}{9}+\binom{13}{8} \\
&= 2(\binom{10}{7}+2\binom{11}{8})+2(2\binom{10}{7})+\binom{12}{9}+\binom{13}{8} \\
&= 2\binom{10}{7}+4\binom{11}{8}+\binom{12}{9}+\binom{13}{8} \\
\end{align*}

We are given that $\binom{15}{8}=6435$, so we can use Pascal's Identity again to find $\binom{13}{8}$:

\begin{align*}
\binom{13}{8} &= \binom{12}{8}+\binom{12}{7} \\
&= \binom{12}{8}+\binom{11}{7}+\binom{12}{7} \\
&= \binom{12}{8}+\binom{11}{8}+\binom{10}{7}
\end{align*}

Now we can substitute in all the values we know:

\begin{align*}
\binom{15}{10} &= 2\binom{10}{7}+4\binom{11}{8}+\binom{12}{9}+\binom{13}{8} \\
&= 2\binom{10}{7}+4\cdot \frac{\binom{16}{9}-\binom{15}{8}}{7}+\frac{\binom{16}{10}-\binom{15}{8}}{9}+\binom{13}{8} \\
&= 2\binom{10}{7}+4\cdot \frac{11440-6435}{7}+\frac{8008-6435}{9}+\binom{12}{8}+\binom{11}{8}+\binom{10}{7} \\
&= 1206 \\
\end{align*}

Therefore, $\binom{15}{10}=\boxed{1206}$.
